    <div class="lesson-content-title col-xs-12">E<sub>rest</sub>=m<sub>0</sub>c<sup>2</sup> for a Particle at Rest</div>
  <div class="lesson-content-body col-xs-12 ">

      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-6">
          <div class="lesson-content-memo"> Just rest mass </div>   

          A particle of matter at rest has <span class="lesson-content-mass">mass</span>, so equivalently, 
          we can also say that it has <span class="lesson-content-energy">energy</span>. 
        This is a static situation; there is <strong>no physical process of change</strong> occurring.
        There is no process of conversion of <span class="lesson-content-energy">energy</span> to <span class="lesson-content-mass">mass</span> or vice versa, 
        so it is essentially only a linguistic issue whether the term <span class="lesson-content-mass">mass</span> 
        or <span class="lesson-content-energy">energy</span> is used.
        The symbol <span class="lesson-content-speedlight">'c'</span> is NOT the speed of the particle, it is acting as a conversion factor.
        <br/><br/>
        The equations needed for a particle at rest are:
        <ul>
            <li><span class="lesson-content-energy">E<sub>0</sub></span> =
                <span class="lesson-content-mass">m<sub>0</sub></span>
            <span class="lesson-content-speedlight">c</span><sup>2</sup>
            </li>
            <li>1 eV = 1.602 x 10<sup>-19</sup>J </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      
